Preheat your #oven{} to 220°C/200°C fan/gas mark 7.

Halve, peel and thinly slice the @onion{1}. Peel and grate the @garlic{2%cloves} (or use a #garlic press{}).

Drain and rinse the @lentils{1} in a #sieve{}.

Heat a drizzle of @oil{} in a #medium saucepan{} on medium heat.

Once hot, add the onion and season with @salt{} and @pepper{}. Fry, stirring occasionally, until golden, ~{8-10%minutes}.

Add the @sugar{1/2%tsp} and cook until caramelised, ~{1-2%minutes} more.

Halve any large cauliflower florets and pop them onto a #large baking tray{}.

Drizzle with @oil{}, season with @salt{} and @pepper{}, then sprinkle over the @nigella seeds{1} and half the @North Indian style spice mix{1}. Toss to coat, then spread out in a single layer.

When the oven is hot, roast on the top shelf until golden brown and tender, ~{15-20%minutes}. Turn halfway through.

Once the onion has caramelised, add the garlic, @tomato puree{30} and remaining North Indian style spice mix to the pan. Stir-fry for ~{1%minute}.

Stir in the @coconut milk{200}, @vegetable stock paste{10}, lentils and @water{100}(for the dal), then bring to a simmer and cook until thickened, ~{8-10%minutes}. Add a splash of water if it gets too thick.

Meanwhile, halve the @lime{1/2}.

Once thickened, add the @baby spinach{40} to the dal a handful at a time until wilted and piping hot, ~{2-3%minutes}.

Remove from the heat and squeeze in some lime juice. Taste and add salt, pepper and more lime juice if needed.

Spoon the dal into your #serving bowls{} and top with the roasted cauliflower.

Enjoy!